<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>How Terrorist Groups Are Using A.I. to Gain an Edge in Battle</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/10/us/politics/ai-terrorism-boko-haram-nigeria.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>A.I. chatbots are not just a propaganda tool for violent extremists but are aiding in bomb construction and attack planning, new research finds.</description><dc:creator>Dustin Volz and Eric Schmitt</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2026 13:14:31 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Terrorism</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer security</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">3-D Printers</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Al Qaeda</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Anthropic</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Boko Haram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Center for Strategic and International Studies</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">DeepSeek</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Pentagon</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ISIS</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">ISIL</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Islamic State</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Islamic State West African Province</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">x.ai</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nigeria</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/08/multimedia/00dc-aiterror-01-kphj/00dc-aiterror-01-kphj-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Joris Bolomey/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>Nigerian soldiers training at a military base in Monguno, Nigeria, last year amid a surge in attacks by jihadists. Extremist groups like Boko Haram are turning to A.I. for tactical on-the-ground advantages, highlighting a broader challenge for the A.I. industry.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta Launches New A.I. Model as Global Technology Race Heats Up</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/meta-muse-spark-artificial-intelligence.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>For the first time, the company will offer a paid version of the service, a departure from its longtime philosophy of giving its A.I. away for free.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 09 Jul 2026 18:11:42 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Alexandr Wang</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/09/multimedia/09-biz-meta-ai-whbv/09-biz-meta-ai-whbv-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600-v2.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Eric Helgas for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>The paid product opens up a new revenue stream for Meta, which is planning to spend tens of billions of dollars on artificial intelligence this year.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>How to Turn Your Phone Into a Personal Health Dashboard</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/07/09/technology/personaltech/iphone-android-health-tracking.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Free apps from Google, Samsung and Apple can help you track your diet, exercise and well-being — and provide vital information during emergencies.</description><dc:creator>J. D. Biersdorfer</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 09 Jul 2026 09:02:09 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Smartphone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Android</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">None</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">iPhone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Samsung</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Emergency medicine</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nutrition</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Exercise</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Fitness</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/07/08/technology/personaltech/08BIZ-TECHTIP-TOPART/08BIZ-TECHTIP-TOPART-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Google; Samsung; Apple</media:credit><media:description>From left, the Google Health, the Samsung Health and Apple’s Health apps offer plenty of tools and features to help you manage your diet, exercise and personal safety.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>